{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17653679","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17653679"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:47:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:47:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18588"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18588","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18588"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.11,0.05,0.05,0.74]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11320"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79771"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11320","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11320"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18588"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65076"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10385"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26234"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26241"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79771"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe cerebral cortex contains multiple regions involved in auditory processing. These regions work together to enable humans to perceive and understand sounds from their environment.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of the auditory association area?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Generates internal speech sounds","Detects sound frequency changes","Processes raw auditory signals","Maintains balance and equilibrium","Interprets complex sound patterns and speech"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Einterprets complex sound patterns and speech\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary function of the auditory association area, located in the superior temporal gyrus. This region processes complex auditory information beyond simple sound detection, allowing us to recognise and understand meaningful sounds including human speech.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenerates internal speech sounds\u003C/strong\u003E - This is primarily a function of Broca\u0027s area in the frontal lobe\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetects sound frequency changes\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a function of the primary auditory cortex, not the association area\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProcesses raw auditory signals\u003C/strong\u003E - This occurs in the primary auditory cortex and subcortical auditory pathway\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaintains balance and equilibrium\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a function of the vestibular system and cerebellum\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe auditory association area receives processed information from the primary auditory cortex and integrates it with other sensory and cognitive inputs to create meaningful interpretations of sounds. This includes speech comprehension, music appreciation, and recognition of environmental sounds.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The auditory association area is located in the superior temporal gyrus and processes complex sound patterns including speech.","Wernicke\u0027s area, part of the auditory association cortex, is crucial for language comprehension.","The auditory association area integrates auditory information with other sensory inputs for meaningful interpretation."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65076"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18588"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65076","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65076"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T16:59:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T17:01:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11320"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79771"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"positio